vercel/ai#10329.body:
### Description

#### Problem statement

I’m using the Vercel AI SDK v6 agent abstraction and would like to use provider-side cached system messages (e.g. [Anthropic cache control](https://v6.ai-sdk.dev/providers/ai-sdk-providers/anthropic#cache-control), but the current agent API only seems to support plain instructions: string on the agent declaration. To use cached system messages, I need to construct `ModelMessage[]` / `SystemModelMessage[]` with cache control metadata, but that’s only possible when calling agent.stream directly. I’d like to be able to define these system messages on the agent itself.

#### Current behavior

Agent declaration accepts instructions: string, but not structured model messages:

```
const chatAgent = new ToolLoopAgent({
  model: anthropic("claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929"),
  // Only string instructions supported here
  instructions: 'You are a helpful assistant...',
  // ...
});

// Later, in a workflow:
const result = await chatAgent.stream({
  messages: [
    { role: 'user', content: 'Hello!' },
  ],
});

```

To use Anthropic cache control for system messages (per docs: [AI SDK Anthropic Cache Control](https://v6.ai-sdk.dev/providers/ai-sdk-providers/anthropic#cache-control)), I instead need to construct SystemModelMessage[] and pass them into agent.stream, bypassing the agent’s instructions field:

```
const result = await chatAgent.stream({
  messages: [
    {
      role: "system",
      content: "You are a helpful assistant...",
      cacheControl: { type: 'ephemeral' }, // Anthropic cache control
    } satisfies SystemModelMessage,
    {
      role: "user",
      content: "Hello!",
    },
  ],
});
```

This works, but it means:
- The system behavior (and cache configuration) lives in the call site instead of in the agent definition.
- I can’t declaratively define or reuse cached system messages at the agent level.

#### Expected behavior

I’d like to be able to define the system messages in the agent declaration using ModelMessage[] or SystemModelMessage[], so I can attach cache control metadata (and other provider-specific properties) there.

Example of a possible API:

```
// Pseudo code – desired API
const chatAgent = new ToolLoopAgent({
  model: anthropic("claude-sonnet-4-5-20250929"),

  // support `systemMessages` in addition to `instructions`
  systemMessages: [
    {
      role: 'system',
      content: 'You are a helpful assistant...',
      cacheControl: { type: 'ephemeral' },
    } satisfies SystemModelMessage,
  ],
});

// Then call site stays simple:
const result = await chatAgent.stream({
  messages: [
    { role: 'user', content: 'Hello!' },
  ],
});
```

Only `instructions` or `systemMessages` should be specified at the same time.

This would allow users to leverage provider-level system message caching (e.g., Anthropic cache control as described in [AI SDK Anthropic Cache Control](https://v6.ai-sdk.dev/providers/ai-sdk-providers/anthropic#cache-control)) while keeping the agent abstraction as the single place where system behavior and caching strategy are defined.

