vercel/ai#11268.body:
### Description

In order to maintain type safety on the frontend and backend, [it seems recommended](https://ai-sdk.dev/docs/reference/ai-sdk-core/ui-message#type-safety) to define tools in a place that is shared between the backend and frontend. However, it's not possible to keep tool definitions altogether such that the frontend and backend both reference the same definition, because code in a tool's `execute` usually has backend dependencies that can't be bundled into the frontend.

For example, if I want to define the getWeather tool, but the execution relies on some backend code, I can't define the `tool()` in a shared package that will be used on the frontend.

```ts
// shared package

export const mytools = {
  getWeather: tool({
    inputSchema: {},
    // can't define execute here, relies on backend services that I can't have/don't want bundled on the frontend
  }),
}

export type MyTools = InferUITools<typeof mytools>;

export type MyUIMessage = UIMessage<never, never, MyTools>;
```

The solution I can think of isn't ideal. It involves doing the above for the shared package (no execute), then on the backend redefining the tools:

```ts
// backend

const stream = streamText({
  tools: {
    // Dependency here, if the getWeather wants to change its name, I have to remember to change it here too,
    // it would be a bit better if I can do `[mytools.getWeather.name]: tool()` but it's not exposed on the return
    // return value of tool()
    getWeather: tool({
      inputSchema: mytools.getWeather.inputSchema,
      description: mytools.getWeather.description,
      execute: () => {
        // ...
      }
    })
  }
})
```

Maybe I'm missing something? 

