vercel/ai#11685.body:
## Description

The Anthropic provider's `supportedUrls` configuration only includes `image/*` patterns, missing `application/pdf`. This causes the SDK to download PDF files before sending them to Anthropic, even though Anthropic's API natively supports PDF URLs via `type: "document"` with `source: { type: "url", url: "..." }`.

## Reproduction

**package.json:**
```json
{
  "name": "ai-sdk-pdf-repro",
  "type": "module",
  "dependencies": {
    "@ai-sdk/anthropic": "^2.0.35",
    "@anthropic-ai/sdk": "^0.39.0",
    "ai": "^5.0.101",
    "dotenv": "^17.2.3"
  }
}
```

**repro.mjs:**
```javascript
import { config } from "dotenv";
config();

import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";
import { streamText } from "ai";
import { createAnthropic } from "@ai-sdk/anthropic";

const PDF_URL = "https://arxiv.org/pdf/2401.00001.pdf";
const MODEL = "claude-sonnet-4-20250514";

async function testNativeAnthropicAPI() {
  console.log("=== Testing Native Anthropic API ===\n");
  const client = new Anthropic();

  const response = await client.messages.create({
    model: MODEL,
    max_tokens: 1024,
    messages: [
      {
        role: "user",
        content: [
          { type: "document", source: { type: "url", url: PDF_URL } },
          { type: "text", text: "What is the title of this paper?" },
        ],
      },
    ],
  });

  console.log("✅ Native Anthropic API works!");
  console.log("Response:", response.content[0].text);
}

async function testVercelAISDK() {
  console.log("\n=== Testing Vercel AI SDK ===\n");
  const anthropic = createAnthropic();

  try {
    const result = await streamText({
      model: anthropic(MODEL),
      messages: [
        {
          role: "user",
          content: [
            { type: "file", data: new URL(PDF_URL), mediaType: "application/pdf" },
            { type: "text", text: "What is the title of this paper?" },
          ],
        },
      ],
    });

    for await (const chunk of result.textStream) process.stdout.write(chunk);
    console.log("\n✅ Vercel AI SDK worked!");
  } catch (error) {
    console.log("❌ Vercel AI SDK failed!");
    console.log("Error:", error.message);
  }
}

async function testWithWorkaround() {
  console.log("\n=== Testing with experimental_download workaround ===\n");
  const anthropic = createAnthropic();

  const result = await streamText({
    model: anthropic(MODEL),
    messages: [
      {
        role: "user",
        content: [
          { type: "file", data: new URL(PDF_URL), mediaType: "application/pdf" },
          { type: "text", text: "What is the title of this paper?" },
        ],
      },
    ],
    experimental_download: async (downloads) => {
      console.log("📥 SDK requested downloads:");
      downloads.forEach((d, i) => {
        console.log(`   ${i + 1}. URL: ${d.url}`);
        console.log(`      isUrlSupportedByModel: ${d.isUrlSupportedByModel}`);
      });
      console.log("⏭️  Returning null to skip download\n");
      return downloads.map(() => null);
    },
  });

  for await (const chunk of result.textStream) process.stdout.write(chunk);
  console.log("\n✅ Workaround works!");
}

await testNativeAnthropicAPI();
await testVercelAISDK();
await testWithWorkaround();
```

## Actual Output

```
=== Testing Native Anthropic API ===

✅ Native Anthropic API works!
Response: The title of this paper is "Sector Rotation by Factor Model and Fundamental Analysis."

=== Testing Vercel AI SDK ===

❌ Vercel AI SDK failed!
Error: Failed to download https://arxiv.org/pdf/2401.00001.pdf: TypeError: terminated

=== Testing with experimental_download workaround ===

📥 SDK requested downloads:
   1. URL: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2401.00001.pdf
      isUrlSupportedByModel: false
⏭️  Returning null to skip download

The title of this paper is "Sector Rotation by Factor Model and Fundamental Analysis."
✅ Workaround works!
```

**Key observation:** `isUrlSupportedByModel: false` for the PDF URL proves that PDF is not in `supportedUrls`. The native Anthropic API successfully fetches the same URL, but the SDK fails because it attempts to download first.

## Root Cause

```javascript
// @ai-sdk/anthropic/src/anthropic-provider.ts
supportedUrls: () => ({
  'image/*': [/^https?:\/\/.*$/]
})
```

The Anthropic provider already has correct conversion logic for PDF URLs - if `part.data instanceof URL`, it creates `{ type: "document", source: { type: "url", url: "..." } }`. But PDFs get downloaded before reaching this code because `application/pdf` is not in `supportedUrls`.

## Proposed Fix

```javascript
supportedUrls: () => ({
  'image/*': [/^https?:\/\/.*$/],
  'application/pdf': [/^https?:\/\/.*$/]
})
```

## Impact

- **Memory pressure** - Large PDFs loaded into server memory unnecessarily
- **Latency** - Extra network hop before sending to Anthropic  
- **Failures** - Downloads can fail even when Anthropic can access the URL
- **Presigned URL issues** - S3 presigned URLs often fail when downloaded by the SDK

## Workaround

```typescript
experimental_download: async (downloads) => downloads.map(() => null)
```

## Environment

- `@ai-sdk/anthropic`: 2.0.35 (verified main branch still has this issue)
- `ai`: 5.0.101
- Node.js: 20.x

## Related Issues

- #7245, #8986, #9205

## References

- [Anthropic PDF Support Documentation](https://docs.anthropic.com/en/docs/build-with-claude/pdf-support)

vercel/ai#11720.body:
### Description

## TL;DR

When nesting `ToolLoopAgent` instances, child agent loop iteration spans escape to the parent agent's level, causing trace structure confusion.
**Root cause**: OpenTelemetry context is lost at async generator `yield` boundaries.
**Solution**: Use `context.with()` in the `recordSpan` function to explicitly maintain context propagation.

---

## Environment

- **AI SDK Version**: 
  - `"ai: "6.0.15"`
  - `"@ai-sdk/google": "^3.0.6"`
  - `"@ai-sdk/provider": "^3.0.0"`
  - `"@ai-sdk/react": "^3.0.3"`
- **Framework**: Next.js 16.0.10
- **React Version**: 19.2.3
- **Telemetry Provider**: Langfuse (`langfuse-vercel@3.38.6`)
- **Node.js**: v20.x
- **Architecture**: Multi-agent system (ToolLoopAgent calling another ToolLoopAgent as a tool)

## Description

When nesting `ToolLoopAgent` instances with `experimental_telemetry` enabled, **the initial tool call nesting is correct**, but **subsequent loop iterations of the child agent escape to the parent agent's level**, making it difficult to distinguish between parent and child agent operations.

## Current Behavior

### Actual Trace Structure (Langfuse UI)

```
main-agent (6m 24s)
│
├── [main-agent Step 1] ai.streamText.doStream (17s)
│   Decision: call sub_agent
│
├── [main-agent Step 2] ai.streamText.doStream (5m 57s)
│   └── ai.toolCall sub_agent (5m 45s) ← ✅ Correctly nested!
│       └── ai.streamText (5m 45s)
│           └── ai.streamText.doStream (5m 9s) ← Child agent initial reasoning
│
├── [❌ ESCAPED] ai.streamText.doStream (9.26s) ← This is child Step 2, but at top level!
│   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.40s)
│   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.72s)
│   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.32s)
│   └── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.53s)
│
├── [❌ ESCAPED] ai.streamText.doStream (17.29s) ← Child Step 3, still at top level!
│   └── ai.toolCall reflect_tool
│
└── [❌ ESCAPED] ai.streamText.doStream (9.22s) ← Child Step 4, still at top level!
    ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.72s)
    └── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.33s)
```

### Issue Analysis

1. ✅ **Initial nesting is correct**: `ai.toolCall sub_agent` is properly nested under main-agent Step 2
2. ✅ **Child agent's first doStream is also nested correctly**: Inside `ai.toolCall sub_agent`
3. ❌ **But subsequent child agent loop iterations escaped**:
   - Child Step 2 (with tool calls) appears at main-agent's top level
   - Child Step 3 (reflect_tool) also at top level
   - Child Step 4 (more tool calls) still at top level
4. ❌ **Result**: Parent and child agent loops are mixed at the same level, very confusing

## Expected Behavior

All child agent loop iterations should be nested inside `ai.toolCall sub_agent`:

```
main-agent (6m 24s)
│
├── [Step 1] ai.streamText.doStream (17s)
│
├── [Step 2] ai.streamText.doStream (5m 57s)
│   └── ai.toolCall sub_agent (5m 45s)
│       └── sub-agent complete execution ← All child operations should be here
│           │
│           ├── [Sub Step 1] ai.streamText.doStream (5m 9s)
│           │   Decision: call multiple searches
│           │
│           ├── [Sub Step 2] ai.streamText.doStream (9.26s) ← Should be here!
│           │   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.40s)
│           │   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.72s)
│           │   ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.32s)
│           │   └── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.53s)
│           │
│           ├── [Sub Step 3] ai.streamText.doStream (17.29s) ← Should be here!
│           │   └── ai.toolCall reflect_tool
│           │
│           └── [Sub Step 4] ai.streamText.doStream (9.22s) ← Should be here!
│               ├── ai.toolCall search_tool (2.72s)
│               └── ai.toolCall search_tool (3.33s)
│
└── [Step 3] ai.streamText.doStream (main-agent final reasoning)
```

## Reproduction Code

### Parent Agent

```typescript
// main-agent.ts
export async function createMainAgent(model?: string) {
  return new ToolLoopAgent({
    id: "main-agent",
    model: aiGateway(model || "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4"),
    instructions: mainPrompt,
    tools: {
      sub_agent: subAgentTool(),  // Calls child agent
      // ... other tools
    },
    stopWhen: stepCountIs(100),
    experimental_telemetry: {
      isEnabled: true,
      functionId: "main-agent",
      metadata: {
        agentType: "main-agent",
        agentLevel: "L1",
      },
    },
  });
}
```

### Child Agent

```typescript
// sub-agent.ts
export function subAgentTool() {
  return tool({
    description: "Sub-task agent",
    parameters: z.object({
      objective: z.string(),
    }),
    execute: async function* ({ objective }) {
      // Create child agent instance
      const subAgent = new ToolLoopAgent({
        id: "sub-agent",
        model: aiGateway("anthropic/claude-sonnet-4"),
        instructions: subPromptTemplate,
        tools: {
          search_tool: searchTool(),  // Child agent's tools
          reflect_tool: reflectTool(),
        },
        stopWhen: stepCountIs(20),
        experimental_telemetry: {
          isEnabled: true,  // ← Enable to see tool calls
          functionId: "sub-agent",
          metadata: {
            agentType: "sub-agent",
            agentLevel: "L2",
          },
        },
      });

      // Execute child agent
      const result = await subAgent.stream({ prompt: objective });
      return yield* executeSubAgent(result);
    },
  });
}
```

## Root Cause Analysis

### OpenTelemetry Context Lost in Loop

The issue occurs during ToolLoopAgent's loop execution. Here's the simplified flow:

```typescript
// ToolLoopAgent internal execution (pseudo-code)
async stream() {
  // First reasoning - context is correct
  const span1 = startSpan("doStream"); // ✅ Under correct parent span
  const result1 = await doStream();
  span1.end();

  // Loop: tool calls + re-reasoning
  while (result.finishReason === "tool-calls") {
    // Execute tools
    await executeTools(result.toolCalls);

    // Re-reasoning
    const span2 = startSpan("doStream"); // ❌ Context lost, escapes to top level!
    const result2 = await doStream();
    span2.end();
  }
}
```

**The Problem**:

1. On the first call, OpenTelemetry's active context is correct (parent's tool call span)
2. But in subsequent loop iterations, the active context may be lost due to async operations or generators
3. This causes subsequent spans to be created at the wrong level (escaping to top level)

### Likely Causes

1. **Async generator context propagation**:
   - `tool.execute` returns an async generator
   - OpenTelemetry context may be lost at generator `yield` boundaries
2. **ToolLoopAgent internal implementation**:
   - Each loop iteration may create a new execution context
   - Not properly bound to the initial parent span
3. **Telemetry middleware scope**:
   - `experimental_telemetry` may only establish context on the initial call
   - Loop iterations don't maintain this context

## Source Code Analysis

### Call Chain

The issue occurs in the following call chain:

```
ToolLoopAgent.stream()
  └─> streamText()
      └─> runToolsTransformation()  // packages/ai/src/generate-text/run-tools-transformation.ts
          └─> executeToolCall()     // packages/ai/src/generate-text/execute-tool-call.ts
              └─> recordSpan()      // packages/ai/src/telemetry/record-span.ts
                  └─> executeTool() // packages/provider-utils/src/types/execute-tool.ts
                      └─> for await (const part of stream)  // ❌ yield boundary causes context loss
                          └─> child agent.stream()
                              └─> subsequent loop spans escape to top level
```

### Key Code Locations

#### 1. Tool Execution Entry (`packages/ai/src/generate-text/execute-tool-call.ts`)

```typescript
export async function executeToolCall<TOOLS extends ToolSet>({...}) {
  return recordSpan({
    name: 'ai.toolCall',  // ← Creates tool call span (parent span)
    tracer,
    fn: async span => {
      const stream = executeTool({...});  // ← Calls async generator

      // ❌ Key issue: iterating async generator
      // At yield boundaries, OpenTelemetry's active context is lost
      for await (const part of stream) {
        if (part.type === 'preliminary') {
          onPreliminaryToolResult?.({...});
        } else {
          output = part.output;
        }
      }
      // ...
    },
  });
}
```

#### 2. recordSpan Implementation (`packages/ai/src/telemetry/record-span.ts`)

```typescript
export async function recordSpan<T>({...}) {
  return tracer.startActiveSpan(
    name,
    { attributes: await attributes },
    async span => {
      try {
        // ❌ fn executes here, but context is not explicitly bound to async generator
        // The active context established by `tracer.startActiveSpan` 
        // doesn't automatically persist across async generator yield boundaries
        const result = await fn(span);

        if (endWhenDone) span.end();
        return result;
      } catch (error) {
        recordErrorOnSpan(span, error);
        span.end();
        throw error;
      }
    },
  );
}
```

#### 3. executeTool Implementation (`packages/provider-utils/src/types/execute-tool.ts`)

```typescript
export async function* executeTool<INPUT, OUTPUT>({...}) {
  const result = execute(input, options);

  if (isAsyncIterable(result)) {
    let lastOutput: OUTPUT | undefined;
    // ❌ Yield here causes context loss
    // Each `yield` pauses execution, when resumed OpenTelemetry's active context may have changed
    for await (const output of result) {
      lastOutput = output;
      yield { type: 'preliminary', output };  // ← yield boundary
    }
    yield { type: 'final', output: lastOutput! };
  } else {
    yield { type: 'final', output: await result };
  }
}
```

### Root Cause

**OpenTelemetry's `startActiveSpan` does not automatically maintain context across async generator yield boundaries.**

Execution flow:

1. ✅ **First execution**:
   - `recordSpan` creates `ai.toolCall` span and sets it as active context
   - Child agent's first `streamText.doStream` span is correctly nested (within same context)
2. ❌ **After yield**:
   - `executeTool` returns preliminary results via `yield`
   - JavaScript pauses async generator execution
   - When child agent continues loop and creates new spans, OpenTelemetry cannot find the original active context
   - New spans are created in default root context, causing escape
3. ❌ **Subsequent loops**:
   - All subsequent child agent steps execute in wrong context
   - All spans appear at top level instead of nested under `ai.toolCall`

**OpenTelemetry Documentation**: According to [OpenTelemetry Context Propagation](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/concepts/signals/traces/#context-propagation), context needs to be explicitly propagated across async boundaries (especially async generator yields).

## Proposed Solution

Explicitly maintain OpenTelemetry context in `packages/ai/src/telemetry/record-span.ts` to ensure context isn't lost at async generator yield boundaries:

```typescript
import { context, Span, Tracer, Attributes } from '@opentelemetry/api';

export async function recordSpan<T>({
  name,
  tracer,
  attributes,
  fn,
  endWhenDone = true,
}: {
  name: string;
  tracer: Tracer;
  attributes: Attributes | PromiseLike<Attributes>;
  fn: (span: Span) => Promise<T>;
  endWhenDone?: boolean;
}) {
  return tracer.startActiveSpan(
    name,
    { attributes: await attributes },
    async span => {
      // ✅ Capture current context (including active span)
      const ctx = context.active();

      try {
        // ✅ Execute within context.with to ensure async generator yields don't lose context
        const result = await context.with(ctx, () => fn(span));

        if (endWhenDone) {
          span.end();
        }

        return result;
      } catch (error) {
        recordErrorOnSpan(span, error);
        span.end();
        throw error;
      }
    },
  );
}
```

**Why This Works**:

1. **Covers all scenarios**: Tool execution call chain is `executeToolCall` → `recordSpan` → `executeTool`, fixing at the `recordSpan` layer captures all tool executions
2. **Centralized change**: Only one file needs modification, impact is controllable
3. **Follows best practices**: OpenTelemetry recommends binding context when creating spans ([documentation](https://opentelemetry.io/docs/concepts/signals/traces/#context-propagation))

**Alternative Approach**:

If you prefer to solve it at the root level, you could modify the `executeTool` function in `packages/provider-utils/src/types/execute-tool.ts`, but this requires:

- Modifying the lower-level dependency package `@ai-sdk/provider-utils`
- Publishing a new version with more comprehensive testing
- Given that `executeTool` only has one usage point within the AI SDK (`executeToolCall`), the benefit is limited

## Related Information

Async generator context propagation is a known challenge in the OpenTelemetry community:

- [Context lost in async generators](https://github.com/open-telemetry/opentelemetry-js/issues/1936)
- [Context propagation across yield boundaries](https://github.com/open-telemetry/opentelemetry-js/discussions/3201)

LangChain encountered similar nested agent tracing issues early on and solved it with an explicit `CallbackManager`.

### Expected Span Tree

```
parent
├── step-1: doStream
├── step-2: doStream
│   └── tool-call: call_child
│       └── child (all of these should be nested here)
│           ├── step-1: doStream
│           ├── tool-call: simple_tool
│           └── step-2: doStream
└── step-3: doStream (parent agent final response)
```

## Additional Information

### Impact

This issue affects:

- ✅ All multi-agent architectures using nested ToolLoopAgent
- ✅ Any child agent requiring loop execution (called via tool.execute)
- ✅ Production observability and debugging capabilities
- ✅ Trace-based cost analysis and performance optimization

---

**This is a context propagation bug that severely impacts nested agent observability. We hope the team can prioritize this fix!**

## Checklist

- [x] Searched existing issues - no duplicates found
- [x] Provided screenshots and detailed trace structure comparison
- [x] Provided reproducible code example
- [x] Analyzed root cause
- [x] Proposed viable solution with explanation
