vercel/ai#12786.body:
### Description

## Description
When `toolChoice` is set to a specific tool (e.g. `{ type: 'tool', toolName: 'foo' }`), the SDK passes that constraint to the provider but does not enforce it in runtime validation of returned tool calls.

*Note on provider behavior:*
Some providers enforce tool-choice constraints server-side (e.g. Groq), which can mask this issue. This bug report uses Amazon Bedrock for reproduction to demonstrate the SDK-side enforcement gap.

This can execute unintended tools despite explicit caller constraints. For apps using `toolChoice` as a safety/control boundary, this is a correctness and safety bug.

## Steps to reproduce

```ts
import { bedrock } from '@ai-sdk/amazon-bedrock';
import { generateText, stepCountIs, tool } from 'ai';
import { z } from 'zod';

const tools = {
  getWeatherByCity: tool({
    description: 'Get current weather by city name',
    inputSchema: z.object({ city: z.string() }),
    execute: async ({ city }) => ({ city, forecast: 'sunny', temperatureC: 22 }),
  }),
  getWeatherByCoords: tool({
    description: 'Get current weather by latitude/longitude coordinates',
    inputSchema: z.object({ latitude: z.number(), longitude: z.number() }),
    execute: async ({ latitude, longitude }) => ({
      latitude,
      longitude,
      forecast: 'cloudy',
      temperatureC: 20,
    }),
  }),
  getCurrentWeather: tool({
    description: 'Get current weather from a free-form location string',
    inputSchema: z.object({ location: z.string() }),
    execute: async ({ location }) => ({ location, forecast: 'windy', temperatureC: 19 }),
  }),
  getWeatherForecast: tool({
    description: 'Get weather forecast for the next N days',
    inputSchema: z.object({ location: z.string(), days: z.number().int().min(1).max(7) }),
    execute: async ({ location, days }) => ({
      location,
      days,
      forecast: Array.from({ length: days }, () => 'partly cloudy'),
    }),
  }),
};

const result = await generateText({
  model: bedrock('openai.gpt-oss-20b-1:0'),
  stopWhen: stepCountIs(1),
  temperature: 0,
  toolChoice: { type: 'tool', toolName: 'getWeatherByCity' },
  tools,
  prompt:
    'Use tools to get the current weather in San Francisco.',
});

const calledTools = result.toolCalls.map(call => call.toolName);
const mismatchedCalls = calledTools.filter(name => name !== 'getWeatherByCity');

if (mismatchedCalls.length > 0) {
  console.error(
    `BUG REPRODUCED: model returned tool(s) "${mismatchedCalls.join(', ')}" while toolChoice required "getWeatherByCity".`,
  );
}
