vercel/ai#13595.body:
### Feature Description

Mistral Small 4 introduced a `reasoning_effort` parameter in the Chat Completions API to control the depth of reasoning:

- `"none"` — fast, lightweight responses
- `"high"` — deep, step-by-step reasoning

See: https://mistral.ai/fr/news/mistral-small-4

### Current Behavior

The `@ai-sdk/mistral` provider's `MistralLanguageModelOptions` schema doesn't include `reasoning_effort`, so there's no way to pass it through `providerOptions`. The current workaround requires a custom `fetch` wrapper to inject the parameter into the request body:

```ts
const mistral = createMistral({
  apiKey: process.env.MISTRAL_API_KEY,
  fetch: async (url, init) => {
    if (init?.body && typeof init.body === "string") {
      const body = JSON.parse(init.body);
      body.reasoning_effort = "high";
      return fetch(url, { ...init, body: JSON.stringify(body) });
    }
    return fetch(url, init);
  },
});
```

### Expected Behavior

Support `reasoning_effort` as a first-class provider option:

```ts
await generateText({
  model: mistral("mistral-small-latest"),
  providerOptions: {
    mistral: {
      reasoningEffort: "high",
    },
  },
  prompt: "...",
});
```

### Additional context

- Other providers (`@ai-sdk/openai`, `@ai-sdk/groq`, `@ai-sdk/xai`, `@ai-sdk/openai-compatible`) already support a similar `reasoningEffort` option
- The Mistral provider already handles reasoning response parsing (thinking blocks) — this is just about the request-side parameter
- Affects `@ai-sdk/mistral` v3.0.24+
